															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drclef" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(213153); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=213153&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610161927" alt="DrClef" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=213153)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drclef" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(213153); return false;" >DrClef</a></span> <span class="odate time_1427737344 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Mar 2015 17:42</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2260535">
									

<p>Kalinin: Here are my thoughts. You don't need to agree with me.</p>
<p>&quot;This is senior staff telling people this is how it's going to be now.&quot; Project Resurrection is a canon. &quot;There is no one single canon&quot; still applies.</p>
<p>&quot;This is a top-down staff mandate.&quot; Not exactly. Project Resurrection was mostly inspired by the fact that the off-site fandom's favorite elements tended to be stuff like Omega-7, the more creepypasta-esque monsters, and the character-driven stuff. Which made us wonder why there was so little new stuff in that line being written for on wiki.</p>
<p>Conclusion; there is currently no safe space for that kind of content here. Which is where the top-down staff mandate comes in: &quot;We're letting that stuff back onto the site as long as it's written well.&quot; If Project Res takes off and becomes popular, more power to it. If it does not, then we'll shrug our shoulders and quietly put it aside.</p>

							</div>

								
					
