		<div class="post" id="post-2260706">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2260706)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2260706">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1427754172 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Mar 2015 22:22</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2260706">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;wall&nbsp;of&nbsp;text</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;hide&nbsp;wall&nbsp;of&nbsp;text</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>You don't need to agree with me.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Very kind of you.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;This is senior staff telling people this is how it's going to be now.&quot; Project Resurrection is a canon. &quot;There is no one single canon&quot; still applies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You are correct that Resurrection is one canon of the group that we have on the site. However, it's disingenous to suggest that it's merely one of a bunch, since this one, unlike the others, has a cadre of admins and mods actively flogging it and soliciting site-wide adoption. In the letter, yes, this doesn't change anything. In terms of the message being sent by the people in charge of administering site, well, that's a different matter.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Project Resurrection was mostly inspired by the fact that the off-site fandom's favorite elements tended to be stuff like Omega-7, the more creepypasta-esque monsters, and the character-driven stuff. Which made us wonder why there was so little new stuff in that line being written for on wiki.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Two things trouble me about that. The first being, when did staff make the decision to adjust the site's content in a concerted manner to appeal to the &quot;offsite fandom,&quot; about which we really don't know a whole lot other than what can be scraped together from anecdotal evidence? One can make an argument that if we were to go down that road, it would lead directly away from the recent innovations and creativity that you're supposedly in favor of.</p>
<p>The second thing is that I think you're glossing over the fact that this reflects the personal tastes of a group of staff, and as such this is an attempt to advance that particular vision. I don't think this is a sinister takeover or a malicious attempt at subverting the site, so don't get me wrong here, but conscious or not, this comes across to me as institutionalization of personal preference of a select group of users (albeit longstanding and influential ones).</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Conclusion; there is currently no safe space for that kind of content here.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is almost funny given the concerns raised in other quarters that it's not safe to try anything &quot;new&quot; on the site either. I agree with your premise stated above that there is less SSAA-related material on the site than in the past. That is not in dispute. I do, however, reject entirely the notion that there is &quot;no safe space&quot; for such content. SCP-2000, arguably the harbinger of the &quot;next level&quot; quality of Series III, makes liberal use of established characters such as Dr. Gears (though not in the lolwacky way of some pieces of the past). I've read tales in the past year set in the Bellerverse featuring Dr. Mann, a Dr. Bright murder mystery (that was quite good, btw), stories involving Kain, Lament and Mann, numerous articles referencing Rosen, a rewritten article prominently featuring Dr. Rights, etc. etc. etc.</p>
<p>It is demonstrably false that there isn't a place for the content you're envisioning here. Leaving aside the numerous articles like those I just mentioned, if that were true, you wouldn't have been able to get away with the first entry of this very series, seeing as how it was posted in advance of this statement of purpose that you've outlined. The discussion, then, isn't that you want this kind of material to exist on the site. The discussion is really that you want it to exist in <em>higher proportion</em>. That distinction is superficially nitpicky and subtle, but it makes a huge difference in my estimation. Advocating for a safe place for something to merely exist, and if it survives and thrives so be it, is one thing. Advocating for the increased prevalence of something and taking steps to ensure it is quite another.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If Project Res takes off and becomes popular, more power to it. If it does not, then we'll shrug our shoulders and quietly put it aside.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If this were the case, I would be completely with you, and merely register my opinion on each piece on move on. But that's not really what's happening here.</p>
<p>I don't think this going to ruin the site or whatever. But the idea of intervention regarding creative direction in such a direct manner by the staff, whether or not it's &quot;official&quot; by the letter, does not sit well with me at all. I realize that I'm heavily outnumbered on this, but I would encourage this angle to be considered if any future endeavors of this nature are discussed.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

