					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hotcocoanerd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2032511); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2032511&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610161927" alt="HotCocoaNerd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2032511)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hotcocoanerd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2032511); return false;" >HotCocoaNerd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1427737861 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Mar 2015 17:51</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2260545">
									

<p>I would have to disagree with your analysis. The staff involved don't seem to be saying &quot;this is what is going to happen now.&quot; To me it seems more like they are re-opening possible paths for our creativity that, in the past, had been closed because of taboo. Some of the older stuff was highly OTT and would not hold up to today's standards, granted. As I understand it, that was why there was a big push to get away from it, which eventually led to the higher level writing on the site today. Part of that push away was fueled by the deconstruction of what would happen if you tried making Omega-7. This project could be seen as a reconstruction of that older form of writing. Taking the good bits and pieces from the old stuff and applying a Series III level of experience and creativity to it. They aren't telling us that we <em>should</em> do this, just that we <em>can</em>.</p>
<p>E: ninja'd by Clef.</p>

							</div>

								
